  "prompt": "Is there any app like Shazam to get the chord tabs when hearing a song?",
  "response": "While there isn't a perfect, fully automated \"Shazam for chords\" app, there are a few options that attempt to do what you're asking, with varying degrees of accuracy.  Keep in mind that **transcribing music accurately is a very complex task even for humans, so these apps are unlikely to be perfect.** They should be considered tools to help you get started, not a replacement for learning to hear and understand music yourself.\n\nHere are some apps and approaches:\n\n**Apps that Attempt Chord Extraction:**\n\n*   **Moises: The Musician's App (iOS & Android):** This app is probably the closest to what you're looking for. It uses AI to separate tracks (vocals, drums, bass, guitar, etc.) and **attempt to detect chords**. It displays the chords in real-time as the song plays. It's quite powerful and used by many musicians. *Accuracy varies depending on the complexity and clarity of the song.*\n*   **Chordify (Web, iOS & Android):** Chordify analyzes the audio and provides chord diagrams. It's decent, but not always accurate. It focuses on guitar, ukulele, and piano. It's good for quickly getting a basic idea of the chords, but double-check its work!\n*   **Songsterr (Web, iOS & Android):**  Primarily a tab library, but Songsterr has a powerful playback engine. While it doesn't automatically *detect* chords from a song, it allows you to slow down playback, loop sections, and see the chords visually as the music plays. This is invaluable for learning by ear. Search for the song in Songsterr, and even if the tab isn't perfect, the synchronized playback will help you figure it out.\n*   **Ultimate Guitar: Tabs & Chords (Web, iOS & Android):**  Similar to Songsterr, Ultimate Guitar is a massive tab and chord library. Search for the song, find a chord chart, and use their playback features to practice along. Not automatic chord detection, but a fantastic learning resource.\n*   **Capo (macOS & iOS):**  Designed to help you learn songs by ear. It allows you to slow down audio, loop sections, and even isolate certain instruments. While it doesn't automatically generate chords, its analysis tools make it much easier to hear and identify the chords yourself. The iOS version is less feature-rich than the macOS version.\n*   **Riffstation (desktop software - now defunct, but still available from some third party sites):** Riffstation was a very popular program that attempted chord recognition. It's no longer officially supported, and finding a legitimate download can be tricky. *Be cautious downloading software from unofficial sources.*\n\n**Important Considerations and Limitations:**\n\n*   **Accuracy:** As mentioned, these apps are not perfect. The accuracy of chord detection depends heavily on the quality of the recording, the complexity of the song, and the types of instruments involved. Expect to have to correct the chords provided by the app.\n*   **Complexity:** Simple pop songs with clear chord progressions are much easier for these apps to analyze than complex jazz or progressive rock tunes.\n*   **Alternative Tunings:** Most chord detection apps are designed for standard tuning. If a song uses an alternative tuning, the app will likely get the chords wrong.\n*   **Inversions and Voicings:** The apps may only give you the basic root chord (e.g., C, G, Am) and not show the specific inversion or voicing being used. This can significantly impact the sound of the song.\n*   **Learning by Ear:** While these apps can be helpful, don't rely on them completely. Developing your own ear training skills is essential for becoming a well-rounded musician.\n\n**Alternatives and Enhancements:**\n\n*   **Combine Apps:** Use a track separation app like Moises to isolate the guitar part, then use a chord detection app to analyze the isolated track. This can improve accuracy.\n*   **Slow Down the Audio:** Use an app like Capo or the playback features of Songsterr/Ultimate Guitar to slow down the audio without changing the pitch. This makes it much easier to hear the chord changes.\n*   **Learn Music Theory:** A basic understanding of music theory (chord construction, key signatures, etc.) will help you identify chords by ear and correct any errors made by the apps.\n*   **Use a Guitar Tuner:** Ensure your guitar is properly tuned before you start learning a song.\n\n**In summary:**\n\n*   **Moises** is probably the closest to a \"Shazam for chords\" that exists right now.\n*   **Chordify** is another option but may require more corrections.\n*   **Songsterr and Ultimate Guitar** are excellent resources because of their massive tab libraries and synced playback features, even though they don't automatically detect chords.\n\nExperiment with these apps and find the ones that work best for you. Remember that they are tools to *assist* you, not to replace your own musical ear. Good luck!\n",
